s, and the philosophy of history. Here Berlin describes his view of the nature of philosophy, and of its main task: to uncover the various models and presuppositions--the concepts and categories--that men bring to their existence and that help form that existence. Throughout, his writing is informed by his intense consciousness of the plurality of values, the nature of historical understanding, and of the fragility of human freedom in the face of rigid dogma. This new edition adds a number of previously uncollected pieces that throw further light on Berlin's central philosophical concerns, and a revealing exchange of letters with the editor and Bernard Williams about the genesis of the book.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 05. Dez 2022) 0aLogic. 0aPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh  aAbsurdity.  aAge of Enlightenment.  aAlasdair MacIntyre.  aAmbiguity.  aAnalogy.  aAnalytic philosophy.  aArchimedean point.  aAristotle.  aBernard Williams.  aCalculation.  aCategorical proposition.  aCausality.  aConcept.  aConditional sentence.  aConsciousness.  aConsideration.  aCriticism.  aDavid Hume.  aDirect experience.  aEgalitarianism.  aEmpirical evidence.  aEmpirical research.  aEo ipso.  aEpistemology.  aEquality before the law.  aEssence.  aEthics.  aExistence.  aExplanation.  aFallacy.  aFellow.  aGilbert Ryle.  aGrammar.  aHistorical method.  aHuman science.  aHypothesis.  aIdealism.  aIdeology.  aInductive reasoning.  aInference.  aIsaiah Berlin.  aJ. L. Austin.  aLiberalism.  aLinguistic philosophy.  aLogic.  aLogical positivism.  aMathematics.  aMetaphor.  aMorality.  aNarrative.  aNatural and legal rights.  aNatural science.  aNonsense.  aObjectivity (philosophy).  aOn Liberty.  aPhenomenalism.